# Git Commit Messages

When creating commits, follow conventional commit format and these practices.

## Commit hygiene

- One purpose per commit; split unrelated changes
- Commit early and often on feature branches
- Write messages others (and future you) can understand

## Format

```
<type>(<optional scope>): <subject>

<optional body>

<optional footer(s)>
```

## Subject line

- Imperative, present tense, lowercase (e.g. "add", not "added" or "adds")
- Max 50 characters; no trailing period; avoid unnecessary punctuation
- Body (when needed): explain what and why, wrap at 72 characters
- Blank line between subject and body

## Types

| Type | Use for |
|------|---------|
| `feat` | New user-facing feature |
| `fix` | User-facing bug fix |
| `docs` | Documentation only |
| `style` | Formatting; no production logic change |
| `refactor` | Code change that is not a fix or feature |
| `test` | Tests only |
| `chore` | Maintenance (e.g. .gitignore, tooling config) |
| `build` | Build system or dependencies |
| `perf` | Performance improvement |

## Examples

```
fix: prevent racing of requests

Introduce a request id and a reference to the latest request. Dismiss
incoming responses other than from the latest request.

Resolves: #123
```

```
fix: remove string template from client code

It is incompatible with IE
```

```
docs: prepare CHANGELOG for version x.x.x
```

When drafting commit messages for the user, match this format exactly.
